    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:a1830503-9d38-4726-bb73-6d022324d701",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 4-year-old girl who presents to the pediatric emergency department accompanied by her visibly worried mother. She is a small, rosy-cheeked child with curly auburn hair, currently appearing tired and mildly distressed. She is sitting upright on the exam table, clinging to her stuffed rabbit, with noticeable rapid and labored breathing. Her cheeks are flushed, and she has a persistent, productive-sounding cough that makes her wince. Her lips appear slightly dry, and she is intermittently shivering despite the warm room. Her mother also notes that {patientName} has been snoring loudly at night for the past several days, which is new and has been disturbing her sleep. {patientName} also complained of a headache earlier today, pointing to her forehead, though she struggles to articulate it clearly.\n\nAt home, {patientName} attends a local daycare five days a week, where she loves painting, storytime, and playing on the indoor slide. She is an energetic and social child under normal circumstances, but over the past four days she has been increasingly lethargic, refusing meals, and clinging to her mother. Her mother reports she has barely touched her favorite foods — macaroni and cheese and apple slices — which is very out of character.\n\n{patientName} lives in a two-bedroom apartment with her mother, father, and 7-year-old brother. The family has a pet cat, and {patientName} has a known mild allergy to cat dander manifesting as rhinitis and conjunctivitis. The home is in an urban area, and the apartment building is older with some reported dampness in the walls. Her father is a smoker who smokes outside, but the family occasionally travels in a car together after he has smoked.\n\nHer mother first noticed a runny nose and low-grade fever about five days ago, which she initially attributed to a common cold. Over the next two days, the fever spiked to 39.4°C (103°F), and {patientName} developed a worsening cough and began breathing faster than usual. By the time of presentation, her mother noted she seemed to be \"working hard to breathe\" and her lips looked \"a little bluish\" at one point, prompting the emergency visit. The cough has occasionally produced a small amount of blood-tinged sputum (hemoptysis), which alarmed the family greatly.\n\nOn physical examination, {patientName} is febrile at 39.2°C, tachycardic at 132 bpm, tachypneic at 42 breaths per minute, and oxygen saturation is 93% on room air. Auscultation of the lungs reveals decreased breath sounds and dullness to percussion in the right lower lobe, with fine crackles audible. Imaging confirms right lower lobe consolidation consistent with pneumonitis/pneumonia. She is alert and oriented, responding to her mother's voice, though clearly fatigued."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:129d2db4-f539-4f03-9644-29dc4887f2ca",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at 38 weeks gestation via normal vaginal delivery with no significant perinatal complications. Her birth weight was 3.1 kg and she was discharged home after 48 hours. She has met all developmental milestones appropriately and is up to date on her routine vaccinations per the national immunization schedule, including pneumococcal conjugate vaccine (PCV13) and influenza vaccine (last administered 8 months ago).\n\n{patientName} has a history of two prior episodes of otitis media (at ages 2 and 3), both treated successfully with oral amoxicillin. She also had one episode of viral bronchiolitis at age 18 months requiring a short hospital observation stay, representing a prior lower respiratory tract infection and indicating a degree of predisposition to respiratory illness. She had one febrile seizure at age 2 years associated with a viral illness, which resolved spontaneously and has not recurred. She has no history of asthma, chronic lung disease, or confirmed immunodeficiency, though her recurrent respiratory infections suggest a possible maturational immune vulnerability. She has no known surgical history aside from the tympanocentesis documented below.\n\nA notable comorbidity predisposing to this episode is her documented allergy to cat dander (rhinitis, conjunctivitis), which contributes to chronic upper airway mucosal irritation and impaired mucociliary clearance, increasing her susceptibility to lower respiratory tract infections. Passive tobacco smoke exposure from her father further compromises airway defenses. Additionally, {patientName} has been receiving long-term low-dose intranasal corticosteroid therapy (fluticasone) for her allergic rhinitis related to cat dander exposure, as prescribed by her pediatrician. Prolonged use of inhaled/intranasal corticosteroids is a recognized risk factor for impaired local immune defenses and can predispose to respiratory infections including pneumonia.\n\nNotable risk